 distant philanthropy.Aiding Ireland investigates the Irish famine as a foundational moment for normalizing international giving. Anelise Hanson Shrout argues that these diverse men and women found famine relief to be politically useful. Shrout takes readers from Ireland to Britain, across the Atlantic to the United States, and across the Mississippi to Indian Territory, uncovering what was to be gained for each group by participating in global famine relief. Aiding Ireland demonstrates that international philanthropy and aid are never simple, and are always intertwined with politics both at home and abroad.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFood reliefxPolitical aspectszIrelandxHistoryy19th century2DLC. 0aFood reliefxPolitical aspectszIrelandxHistoryy19th century. 0aInternational reliefzIrelandxHistoryy19th century2DLC. 0aInternational reliefzIrelandxHistoryy19th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Social Classes & Economic Disparity.2bisacsh  aBritish empire.  aCorn Laws.  aDublin.  aEurope.  aGlasgow.  aHISTORY.  aIreland.  aIrish famine.  aLiverpool.  aLondon.  aManchester.  aPhilanthropy & Charity.  aSOCIAL SCIENCE.  aSocial Classes & Economic Disparity.  aanti-Irish.  aempire.  afamine.  agreat.  ahumanitarianism.  aimmigration.  ainternational Aid.  aliberal humanitarianism.  anationalism.  aphilanthropy.  apopular politics.  arelief.  atransnational.  aunionism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311075164240uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479824618.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479824618423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479824618/original  a978-3-11-075164-2  New York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024 